\begin_layout Standard
From a physical perspective,
 the main thing that impacts a chain crystal's behavior is called 
\emph on
muonic potential energy
\emph default
,
 or MPE for short.
 In short,
 every link in a chain has an assigned number (which can be positive,
 negative,
 or zero),
 which is the link's MPE,
 and two chains of the same length where each corresponding link has the same MPE are going to behave very similarly,
 so these numbers determine almost all the information about the chain.
 As a consequence,
 these numbers are very important!
 Theoretically,
 the MPE of the links of a chain are determined by the following factors:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The temperature factor of the crystal,
 which is 
\emph on
always
\emph default
 a positive number 
\begin_inset Formula $T>0$
\end_inset

 that depends on the environment,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The total energy capacity of the crystal,
 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

,
 which depends on the material the chain is made of,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The link connective factor,
 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

,
 which depends on the material the chain is made of,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The strength of the magnetic field exerted on the crystal,
 if any,
 which is a number (positive,
 negative,
 or zero (if there is no magnetic field)) represented by the letter 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

,
 and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The number of elements in the link.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If you know all of these numbers,
 you can find the MPE of all the links in a chain,
 using the following rules:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The sum of all MPE in a chain is equal to the energy capacity 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If three links are consecutive in a chain and their MPE is respectively 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

,
 they must satisfy the rule:
 
\begin_inset Formula $x+Ty+z=b$
\end_inset

,
 and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The last two links in a chain (away from the telluriumide surface) satisfy the following formula.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 is the MPE of the link at the very end,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is the MPE of the link right before it,
 
\begin_inset Formula $2(1-T)x+y=\mu$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

